<div class="c-home-section js-home-section js-demos <% if (!path.match(/^\/$/)) { %>d-none<% } %>">
    <h2>Welcome to Silk router Home Page</h2>
    <p>Silk router is a library for implementing single page applications like this one.</p>
    <p>
        <pre>
            <code>
    import { router, route } from 'silkrouter';</code>
        </pre>
    </p>
    <p>
        <pre>
            <code>
    route(...);
    router.set(...);</code>
        </pre>
    </p>
    <h3>Installation</h3>
    <p>
        Using <b>node package manager (npm)</b> as follows:
        <pre>
            <code>
    npm install --save silkrouter deparam.js lzstorage</code>
        </pre>
    </p>
    <p>
        Using <b>CDN</b> as follows:
        <pre>
            <code>
    https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/silkrouter@<%=version%>/dist/js/silkrouter.min.js</code>
        </pre>
        Or simply:
        <pre>
            <code>
    https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/silkrouter@<%=version%></code>
        </pre>
    </p>
    <h3>How does it work?</h3>
    <p>Silk router is quite simple to use. It is similar to JavaScript events.</p>
    <p><b>Events:</b></p>
    <pre>
        <code>
    document.querySelector('selector').addEventListener('eventName', handler);</code>
    </pre>
    <p><b>Router:</b></p>
    <pre>
        <code>
    route('path', handler);</code>
    </pre>
    <p><b>Trigger event:</b></p>
    <pre>
        <code>
    document.querySelector('selector').dispatchEvent(new Event('event'));</code>
    </pre>
    <p><b>Trigger route:</b></p>
     <pre>
        <code>
    router.set('path');</code>
    </pre>
    <p></p>
    <p>Silk router uses history push API to update browser history.</p>
    <p>Silk router supports following browsers:</p>
    <p><b>IE10+, Edge, Opera, Safari, Chrome, Firefox</b></p>
</div>